05838nam a22008055i 9781782041351DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820413517 a10.1515/97817820413512doi  a(DE-B1597)676041  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aDA780b.N49 2013 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a941.10222300aNew Perspectives on Medieval Scotland, 1093-1286 /ced. by Matthew H. Hammond. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b8 b/w, 2 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Celtic History ;v3200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of illustrations and tables -- tList of contributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tMaps -- t1 Introduction: The paradox of medieval Scotland, 1093–1286 -- t2 The Scottish ‘political community’ in the reign of Alexander II (1214–49) -- t3 Homo ligius and unfreedom in medieval Scotland -- t4 Scottish royal government in the thirteenth century from an English perspective -- t5 Neighbours, the neighbourhood, and the visnet in Scotland, 1125–1300 -- t6 Cistercian identities in twelfth- and thirteenth-century Scotland: the case of Melrose Abbey -- t7 The language of objects: material culture in medieval Scotland -- t8 Structuring that which cannot be structured: a role for formal models in representing aspects of medieval Scotland -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays consider the changes and development of Scotland at a time of considerable flux in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries.The years between the deaths of King Mael Coluim and Queen Margaret in 1093 and King Alexander III in 1286 witnessed the formation of a kingdom resembling the Scotland we know today, which was a full member of the European club ofmonarchies; the period is also marked by an explosion in the production of documents. This volume includes a range of new studies casting fresh light on the institutions and people of the Scottish kingdom, especially in thethirteenth century. New perspectives are offered on topics as diverse as the limited reach of Scottish royal administration and justice, the ties that bound the unfree to their lords, the extent of a political community in the time of King Alexander II, a view of Europeanization from the spread of a common material culture, the role of a major Cistercian monastery in the kingdom and the broader world, and the idea of the neighbourhood in Scots law. There are also chapters on the corpus of charters and names and the innovative technology behind the People of Medieval Scotland prosopographical database, which made use of over 6000 individual documents from the period. Matthew Hammond is a Research Associate at the University of Glasgow. Contributors: John Bradley, Stuart Campbell, David Carpenter, Matthew Hammond, Emilia Jamroziak, Cynthia Neville, Michele Pasin, Keith Stringer, Alice Taylor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  a1093-1286.  aChartes.  aCistercian Monastery.  aEuropean Club of Monarchies.  aEuropeanization.  aMaterial Culture.  aMatthew Hammond.  aMedieval Scotland.  aNames.  aNeighborhood.  aNew Perspectives.  aPolitical Community.  aScots Law.  aScottish Kingdom.  aTechnology.1 aBradley, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Stuart D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, David X., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpenter, David, ec